In the Sixteenth Satire, nobody condemns any thing, though some condemn every thing. It is fortunate that these ques- tions may be answered one way or another without affecting our judgement of Juvenal's meaning, without materially affect- ing our judgement of his literary form3 for, as we have seen, they must be answered, if at all, with little help from external evidence.
